Several robotic chefs inhabit a kitchen, which they share with inanimate objects such as various ingredients, appliances and utensiles. Their task is to cooperate to produce a threee-course meal.

The situation calculus is a first-order logic formalism for reasoning about dynamic worlds. The state of the world changes as a result of actions being performed in it. In a multi-agent setting, the first argument of the action specifies the agent performing it:

The "state of the world" is represented by a situation, which gives the unique history of actions that have occured. Situations are composed using the function do(). When no actions have occured, the world is in situation s0:
Properties of the world are described by fluents, predicates or functions taking a situation as their final argument:

The special fluent Poss() indicates when actions are possible. The evolution of other fluents is controlled by successor state axioms, which define under what circumstances a fluent becomes true or false.
The situation calculus is modified to allow sets of actions to be performed concurrently. This is crucial for modelling multi-agent systems, where many agents can act at the same time:

To introduce an explicit temporal component, consider actions to be performed at a particular time. do(), Poss() and conflicts() must be modified accordingly:

Natural actions are performed by "the world" and are predictable. They must occur when they are possible, unless something happens to stop them occuring. Situations respecting this requirement are called "legal situations":
legal(s0) <--> True legal(do(c,t,s)) <--> legal(s) and Poss(c,t,s) and start(s) <= t and forall a,t2 [natural(a) and Poss(a,t2,s) --> a in c or t < t2]
Least Natual Time Point: first time at which a natural action can occur in a situation:
lntp(s,t) <--> exists a natural(a) and poss(a,t,s) and start(s) <= t and not [exists a2,t2 natural(a2), poss(a2,t2,s), t2 < t]

Golog programs consist of actions from the situation calculus, combined using operators such as if-then-else, iteration, and nondeterministic choice. The semantics are defined by the macro Do(p,s1,s2), meaning that execution of program p can legally start in s1 and end in s2. Do() is defined recursively for all operators:
Execution is done off-line by proving exists s s.t. Do(p,s0,s), then executing the actions of s.

For single-agent systems, the language Golog has proven very useful:
* Specify behavior as a high-level, non-deterministic program
* Agent searches for a legal program execution
* Amount of non-determinism controlled by programmer
* Easy to encode both procedural knowledge and planning
* Logical semantics enable properties of the program to be proven
Idea: Develop a top-down approach based on Golog to gain these benefits for multi-agent teams
